Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology Suppl. 9: 1-509 (342) recorded the type species as Papilio chromus Cramer, 1780; Edwards, E.D., Newland, J. & Regan, L. 2001. QUALIFICATION: there is doubt about the status of the names monotherm and monotherma; Lower used monotherm in 1907 but emended it to monotherma in 1908; the ICZN (Art. 33(b)(i) allows for an author to correct a name in a corrigendum; Lower's correction was valid in that it is clearly stated and both names are mentioned; it may be, however, that monotherm is an acceptable masculine form of monotherma in which case the name may change with the gender of the generic name; in this case, if the original form of the species name is used irrespective of the gender of the generic name, then monotherm would be used. Braby (2010) pointed out that Lower (1908, p. 312) actually corrected the original spelling to monotherma ?The name is misprinted monotherm.?, and placed it in the genus Hesperilla Hewitson, 1868. The gender of both Telesto Boisduval, 1832, and Hesperilla is feminine, but because monotherm is a noun in apposition the species group name does not need to change. However, since monotherm is an incorrect original spelling that, prior to publication of the Checklist (Atkins & Edwards 1996) has had no usage, Lower?s subsequent correction to monotherma should be maintained

International Code of Zoological Nomenclature, Third Edition, adopted by the XX General Assembly of the International Union of Biological Sciences. London : International trust for Zoological Nomenclature 338 pp. Art. 56(b) stated that two genus-group names are not homonyms if there is only a one-letter difference between them; Edwards, E.D., Newland, J. & Regan, L. 2001. Lepidoptera: Hesperioidea, Papilionoidea. In Wells, A. & Houston, W.W.K. Zoological Catalogue of Australia. Vol. 31.6. Melbourne : CSIRO Publishing, Australia. x 615 pp. as the spelling of Plesionevra Macquart, 1855 (Diptera) has not been emended, and in order to maintain stability in the use of these names, we here follow de Nicéville's decision pending a case to be made to the ICZN on the relative priority of Plesioneura C. & R. Felder, 1862 and Notocrypta de Nicéville, 1889; see Macquart, M. 1855. Nouvelles observations sur les Diptères d'Europe de la tribu des Tachinaires (Fin) (1).
